'''Ella Barksdale Brown''' was an American anti-lynching advocate, educator, and journalist, and a member of the first graduating class of [[Spelman College]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia]].

Brown was born in [[Milledgeville, Georgia]], on June 22, 1871. After marrying John M. Brown in Georgia, she moved to [[New Jersey]] in 1901.<ref name="remember ella">{{cite web|last1=Morgan|first1=Earl|title=Morgan's Corner: Remembering Ella Barksdale Brown|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/voices/index.ssf/2013/02/morgans_corner_remembering_ell.html|accessdate=24 December 2017|date=20 February 2013}}</ref> She was given credit for introducing African-American studies into Jersey City Schools and for designating March 5 as [[Crispus Attucks]] day in New Jersey.

As a journalist, Brown wrote for ''[[The Chicago Defender]]'' and ''[[The New York Amsterdam News]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ella Barksdale Brown Papers|url=http://beinecke.library.yale.edu/about/blogs/african-american-studies-beinecke-library/2008/12/03/ella-barksdale-brown-papers|accessdate=24 December 2017}}</ref>

